                <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed text-gray-600 mb-10 italic border-l-4 border-medicalTeal pl-6">
                    <strong>PRP therapy (Platelet-Rich Plasma therapy)</strong> is a regenerative medical treatment in which a concentrated portion of the patient's own blood — rich in platelets and growth factors — is injected into damaged or ageing tissue to accelerate natural healing and cell regeneration. It is widely used in <a href="../hair-prp-treatment-in-gurgaon">hair restoration</a>, <a href="../face-prp-treatment-in-gurgaon">facial rejuvenation</a>, orthopedic medicine, sports injury recovery, and dentistry.
                </p>

                <p>If you have been researching treatments for hair loss, joint pain, or skin ageing, you have likely come across PRP therapy. Over the last decade, this treatment has moved from elite sports clinics to mainstream dermatology practices, and for good reason. It harnesses your body's own biology rather than relying on synthetic chemicals, making it one of the safest regenerative procedures available today.</p>

                <p>In this comprehensive guide, we break down everything you need to know about PRP therapy — from the science behind it and the different types that exist, to the step-by-step procedure, realistic results timeline, and costs in India.</p>

                <h2>A Brief History of PRP Therapy</h2>

                <p>The concept of using concentrated blood components for healing dates back to the 1970s, when haematologists first developed platelet-rich plasma for transfusion medicine. By the 1980s, PRP found its way into oral and maxillofacial surgery, where dentists used it to promote jawbone regeneration after extractions.</p>

                <p>The real breakthrough came in the early 2000s when professional athletes began using PRP injections to speed up recovery from ligament tears, muscle strains, and tendon injuries. High-profile cases in football, cricket, and tennis brought PRP into the public spotlight. Since then, dermatologists and trichologists have refined the technique for hair restoration and skin rejuvenation, making it one of the most sought-after non-surgical treatments worldwide.</p>

                <p>Today, PRP therapy is backed by hundreds of published clinical studies and is offered in reputed clinics across India, including <a href="../hair-prp-treatment-in-gurgaon">DenceSpot Clinic in Gurgaon</a>.</p>

                <h2>How PRP Therapy Works: The Science Explained</h2>

                <p>To understand PRP therapy, you first need to understand what platelets do. Platelets are tiny blood cells best known for clotting, but they serve a far more important biological function: tissue repair.</p>

                <p>Each platelet contains alpha granules loaded with powerful growth factors, including:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>PDGF (Platelet-Derived Growth Factor):</strong> Stimulates cell replication, blood vessel formation, and collagen synthesis.</li>
                    <li><strong>TGF-beta (Transforming Growth Factor):</strong> Promotes extracellular matrix formation and regulates immune cell activity.</li>
                    <li><strong>VEGF (Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor):</strong> Triggers the formation of new blood vessels, improving blood supply to treated areas.</li>
                    <li><strong>EGF (Epidermal Growth Factor):</strong> Stimulates skin cell growth, wound healing, and collagen production.</li>
                    <li><strong>FGF (Fibroblast Growth Factor):</strong> Drives tissue repair and cell differentiation.</li>
                    <li><strong>IGF (Insulin-like Growth Factor):</strong> Regulates cell growth and plays a role in hair follicle cycling.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Normal blood contains roughly 150,000 to 350,000 platelets per microlitre. In PRP, this concentration is elevated to 3 to 5 times the baseline level. When this concentrated plasma is injected into a target area — whether it is a thinning scalp, an ageing face, or an injured tendon — these growth factors activate dormant stem cells, stimulate collagen production, and promote new blood vessel growth.</p>

                <p>For hair loss specifically, PRP works by prolonging the anagen (active growth) phase of the hair cycle, increasing blood supply to miniaturised follicles, and thickening the dermal papilla. You can read more about how this applies to hair in our detailed guide on <a href="what-is-prp.php">what is PRP for hair</a>.</p>

                <h2>Types of PRP Therapy</h2>

                <p>Not all PRP preparations are the same. The composition of the final product varies based on the preparation method, and this has a meaningful impact on treatment outcomes. There are three main types:</p>

                <h3>1. Pure PRP (P-PRP)</h3>
                <p>Also called leukocyte-poor PRP, this preparation contains a high concentration of platelets with minimal white blood cells (leukocytes). It is the most commonly used form in dermatology, hair restoration, and facial aesthetics. The low leukocyte content means less post-injection inflammation, making it gentler on delicate tissue like the scalp and facial skin.</p>

                <h3>2. Leukocyte-Rich PRP (L-PRP)</h3>
                <p>This variant contains a higher concentration of white blood cells alongside the platelets. The additional leukocytes trigger a stronger inflammatory response, which can be beneficial in orthopedic applications where controlled inflammation helps initiate tendon or ligament repair. It is commonly used for sports injuries, chronic tendinopathies, and joint conditions.</p>

                <h3>3. Leukocyte-Poor PRP (LP-PRP)</h3>
                <p>Similar to pure PRP but prepared using double-spin centrifugation methods that further reduce white blood cell content. This ultra-refined version is preferred for sensitive areas and patients prone to post-treatment swelling. It is increasingly popular in cosmetic dermatology and intra-articular injections for osteoarthritis.</p>

                <p>The type of PRP used at DenceSpot Clinic is selected based on the individual patient's condition, treatment goals, and the area being treated. During your consultation, our specialists determine which preparation will deliver the best results for your specific case.</p>

                <h2>Applications of PRP Therapy</h2>

                <p>PRP therapy has proven effective across a surprisingly wide range of medical and cosmetic applications:</p>

                <h3>Hair Restoration</h3>
                <p>This is one of the most popular applications of PRP in India. PRP injections into the scalp stimulate dormant hair follicles, increase hair thickness, and reduce hair fall. It is effective for androgenetic alopecia (male and female pattern baldness), telogen effluvium, and as a complementary treatment after <a href="../hair-transplant-in-gurgaon">hair transplant surgery</a>. Our complete guide on <a href="prp-hair-treatment-natural-way-to-regrow-hair.php">PRP hair treatment as a natural way to regrow hair</a> covers this in detail.</p>

                <h3>Facial Rejuvenation (Vampire Facial)</h3>
                <p>When applied to the face — either through micro-injections or combined with microneedling — PRP stimulates collagen production, improves skin texture, reduces fine lines, and evens out skin tone. <a href="../face-prp-treatment-in-gurgaon">Facial PRP treatment</a> is particularly popular among patients who prefer natural anti-ageing methods over synthetic fillers.</p>

                <h3>Orthopedics and Sports Medicine</h3>
                <p>PRP injections are used to treat chronic tendon injuries (tennis elbow, Achilles tendinopathy), ligament sprains, muscle tears, and early-stage osteoarthritis. The growth factors accelerate tissue repair and reduce inflammation in injured joints and tendons.</p>

                <h3>Dentistry</h3>
                <p>Oral surgeons use PRP to promote bone regeneration after tooth extractions, dental implant procedures, and jaw reconstruction surgeries. It significantly reduces healing time and improves implant success rates.</p>

                <h3>Wound Healing</h3>
                <p>PRP is applied to chronic non-healing wounds, surgical incisions, and burn injuries to speed up tissue repair and reduce scarring.</p>

