                <h2>PRP Therapy Procedure: Step-by-Step</h2>

                <p>The PRP therapy procedure is straightforward and typically completed within 45 to 60 minutes. Here is what happens during a standard session:</p>

                <h3>Step 1: Consultation and Assessment</h3>
                <p>Before the procedure, the doctor evaluates your medical history, current medications, and the condition being treated. Blood tests may be recommended to rule out any platelet disorders or infections. A detailed scalp or skin analysis is conducted depending on the treatment area.</p>

                <h3>Step 2: Blood Collection</h3>
                <p>A small amount of blood — typically 15 to 30 ml — is drawn from your arm, similar to a routine blood test. This is a quick and painless process that takes less than 5 minutes.</p>

                <h3>Step 3: Centrifugation</h3>
                <p>The collected blood is placed in a specialized centrifuge machine that spins at high speed for 10 to 15 minutes. This separates the blood into three layers: red blood cells at the bottom, platelet-poor plasma at the top, and platelet-rich plasma in the middle. The PRP layer — a golden-yellow concentrate — is carefully extracted.</p>

                <h3>Step 4: Preparation and Activation</h3>
                <p>The extracted PRP may be further processed or activated depending on the protocol. Some clinics add calcium chloride to activate the platelets before injection. The final PRP concentrate contains 3 to 5 times the normal platelet concentration.</p>

                <h3>Step 5: Numbing the Treatment Area</h3>
                <p>A topical anaesthetic cream is applied to the treatment area 20 to 30 minutes before injections. For scalp treatments, a nerve block may also be administered for added comfort.</p>

                <h3>Step 6: PRP Injection</h3>
                <p>Using fine needles, the PRP is injected into the target area at multiple points. For hair restoration, injections are placed across the thinning zones of the scalp at a depth of about 1 to 2 mm. For facial rejuvenation, PRP may be injected or applied after microneedling. The injection process takes approximately 15 to 20 minutes.</p>

                <h3>Step 7: Post-Treatment Care</h3>
                <p>There is no downtime after PRP therapy. Patients can return to normal activities immediately. However, it is advisable to avoid washing the treated area for 24 hours, refrain from strenuous exercise for 48 hours, and stay away from blood-thinning medications for a few days before and after the procedure.</p>

                <h2>Benefits of PRP Therapy</h2>

                <p>PRP therapy offers several advantages over conventional treatments, which explains its growing popularity in India and worldwide:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>100% Natural:</strong> Uses your own blood, eliminating the risk of allergic reactions or immune rejection.</li>
                    <li><strong>Minimally Invasive:</strong> No surgery, no incisions, no stitches. Just a simple blood draw and micro-injections.</li>
                    <li><strong>Zero Downtime:</strong> Walk in during your lunch break and return to work immediately after.</li>
                    <li><strong>Versatile:</strong> Effective for hair loss, skin ageing, joint pain, sports injuries, and more.</li>
                    <li><strong>Clinically Proven:</strong> Supported by extensive published research across multiple medical specialties.</li>
                    <li><strong>Complementary:</strong> Can be safely combined with other treatments such as hair transplant, microneedling, and mesotherapy for enhanced results.</li>
                    <li><strong>Long-lasting Results:</strong> With maintenance sessions, the benefits of PRP therapy can last 12 to 18 months or longer.</li>
                    <li><strong>Affordable:</strong> Significantly less expensive than surgical alternatives, especially in India.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Risks and Side Effects</h2>

                <p>Because PRP is derived from your own blood, it is one of the safest medical procedures available. However, like any injection-based treatment, there are minor risks to be aware of:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Mild Pain or Discomfort:</strong> Some patients experience soreness at the injection site, which resolves within a day or two.</li>
                    <li><strong>Swelling and Redness:</strong> Temporary swelling is common, especially with facial PRP. It typically subsides within 24 to 48 hours.</li>
                    <li><strong>Bruising:</strong> Minor bruising may occur at the blood draw site or injection points.</li>
                    <li><strong>Infection:</strong> Extremely rare when performed in a sterile clinical environment by trained professionals.</li>
                    <li><strong>Nerve or Tissue Injury:</strong> Very uncommon and almost always avoidable with proper technique.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Serious complications are exceptionally rare. PRP therapy is not recommended for patients with blood disorders (thrombocytopenia, platelet dysfunction syndrome), active infections, cancer, chronic liver disease, or those on anticoagulation therapy. Pregnant and breastfeeding women should also avoid PRP.</p>

                <h2>PRP Therapy vs Other Treatments</h2>

                <p>Understanding how PRP compares to alternative treatments helps you make an informed decision:</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Minoxidil (Topical Medication)</h3>
                <p>Minoxidil requires daily application for life and causes side effects like scalp irritation and unwanted facial hair growth in some users. PRP requires only periodic sessions and has virtually no systemic side effects. However, minoxidil is cheaper on a per-month basis and can be used at home. Many patients use both together for maximum benefit.</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Finasteride (Oral Medication)</h3>
                <p>Finasteride is a prescription drug that blocks DHT, the hormone responsible for male pattern baldness. While effective, it carries risks of sexual side effects including decreased libido and erectile dysfunction. PRP has no such hormonal side effects. For patients who cannot tolerate finasteride, PRP is an excellent alternative.</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Hair Transplant</h3>
                <p>A <a href="../hair-transplant-in-gurgaon">hair transplant</a> is a surgical procedure that physically relocates hair follicles from a donor area to bald regions. It is the definitive solution for advanced hair loss but involves surgery, recovery time, and higher cost. PRP is best for early to moderate hair loss and is frequently used as a complementary treatment before and after transplant to improve graft survival and overall density.</p>

                <h3>PRP vs Steroid Injections (for Joint Pain)</h3>
                <p>Corticosteroid injections provide quick pain relief for joint conditions but do not promote actual tissue healing. Repeated steroid injections can even weaken tendons over time. PRP, on the other hand, stimulates genuine tissue repair, making it a better long-term solution for chronic musculoskeletal conditions.</p>

                <h2>Who Should Consider PRP Therapy?</h2>

                <p>PRP therapy may be right for you if you fall into any of the following categories:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Early to Moderate Hair Loss:</strong> Men and women experiencing thinning hair, receding hairlines, or reduced hair density. PRP works best when follicles are still alive but miniaturised.</li>
                    <li><strong>Post Hair Transplant Patients:</strong> To enhance graft survival, speed up healing, and improve the overall density achieved by surgery.</li>
                    <li><strong>Skin Ageing Concerns:</strong> Those looking for a natural alternative to chemical fillers for reducing fine lines, improving skin texture, and restoring a youthful glow.</li>
                    <li><strong>Chronic Joint or Tendon Pain:</strong> Patients with osteoarthritis, tennis elbow, rotator cuff injuries, or plantar fasciitis who have not responded to conventional physiotherapy.</li>
                    <li><strong>Athletes with Sports Injuries:</strong> For faster recovery from muscle tears, ligament sprains, and tendon injuries.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>PRP is <strong>not</strong> suitable for individuals with platelet disorders, active cancer, systemic infections, or those on blood-thinning medications. Always consult a qualified specialist before proceeding.</p>

                <h2>PRP Therapy Results: What to Expect and When</h2>

                <p>Managing expectations is important with PRP therapy. This is not an overnight fix — it works with your body's natural healing timeline.</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Weeks 1 to 2:</strong> Initial healing. Mild shedding may occur in hair PRP patients (a normal sign that follicles are resetting their growth cycle).</li>
                    <li><strong>Weeks 3 to 6:</strong> Reduced hair fall becomes noticeable. Skin patients may see improved texture and subtle glow.</li>
                    <li><strong>Months 2 to 3:</strong> Baby hairs begin appearing in treated areas. Skin shows improved firmness and reduced fine lines.</li>
                    <li><strong>Months 3 to 6:</strong> Significant improvement in hair thickness and density. This is when most patients notice a visible difference.</li>
                    <li><strong>Months 6 to 12:</strong> Peak results achieved with the full course of treatment. Maintenance sessions every 6 to 12 months preserve and build on the gains.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Individual results vary based on age, severity of the condition, overall health, and consistency with the prescribed treatment schedule. Patients who combine PRP with a healthy diet, proper hair care, and any recommended medications tend to see the best outcomes.</p>

                <h2>PRP Therapy Cost in India</h2>

                <p>One of the biggest advantages of getting PRP therapy in India is the cost. Compared to Western countries where a single session can cost USD 500 to 2,000, PRP in India is remarkably affordable:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Scalp PRP (per session):</strong> Rs 3,000 to Rs 12,000</li>
                    <li><strong>Facial PRP / Vampire Facial (per session):</strong> Rs 4,000 to Rs 15,000</li>
                    <li><strong>Joint PRP (per session):</strong> Rs 5,000 to Rs 20,000</li>
                    <li><strong>Full Course (3-4 sessions):</strong> Rs 10,000 to Rs 40,000</li>
                </ul>

                <p>The cost varies depending on the city, clinic infrastructure, the expertise of the doctor, and the type of PRP preparation used. At DenceSpot Clinic in Gurgaon, we offer transparent pricing with no hidden charges. Our PRP treatment packages are designed to be accessible while maintaining international standards of safety and efficacy.</p>

